sentences: David Albert "Panama" Francis (December 21, 1918 – November 13, 2001) was an American swing jazz drummer who played on numerous hit recordings in the 1950s.
Francis was born in Miami, Florida, on December 21, 1918.
Francis first played professionally in the 1930s.
He was part of George Kelly's band from 1934 to 1938, and was then with the Florida Collegians in 1938.
He was part of George Kelly's band from 1934 to 1938, and was then with the Florida Collegians in 1938.
After moving to New York that year, he worked with Tab Smith, Billy Hicks, and Roy Eldridge before the 1940s.
Francis joined Lucky Millinder's big band in 1940, so often played at the Savoy Ballroom.
After leaving Millinder he was with Willie Bryant's band (1946), and then Cab Calloway (1947–52); he was in three short films alongside the latter.
After leaving Millinder he was with Willie Bryant's band (1946), and then Cab Calloway (1947–52); he was in three short films alongside the latter.
From 1963 Francis toured with singer Dinah Shore for five years.
He toured Japan with saxophonist Sam "the Man" Taylor in 1970–71, and appeared on film again in 1972, in Lady Sings the Blues.
He toured Japan with saxophonist Sam "the Man" Taylor in 1970–71, and appeared on film again in 1972, in Lady Sings the Blues.
Back in New York, Francis was part of Sy Oliver's nonet from 1973 to 1975, during which time he also appeared at jazz festivals and toured internationally with other bands.
He revived the Savoy Sultans jazz and dance band in 1979, and he appeared regularly at the Rainbow Room in New York City for eight years from 1980.
He revived the Savoy Sultans jazz and dance band in 1979, and he appeared regularly at the Rainbow Room in New York City for eight years from 1980.
Francis became drummer in the Benny Goodman Quartet for concerts in 1982.
He appeared in the 1994 film The Statesmen of Jazz as a member of the Statesmen of Jazz.
David Francis died on November 13, 2001, following a stroke, at age 82.

sentences: David Albert "Panama" Francis (December 21, 1918 – November 13, 2001) was an American swing jazz drummer who played on numerous hit recordings in the 1950s.
After moving to New York that year, he worked with Tab Smith, Billy Hicks, and Roy Eldridge before the 1940s.
Francis acquired his nickname from Eldridge "at a moment when [Francis] was wearing a panama hat and Eldridge could not remember his new drummer's name".
From 1963 Francis toured with singer Dinah Shore for five years.
He revived the Savoy Sultans jazz and dance band in 1979, and he appeared regularly at the Rainbow Room in New York City for eight years from 1980.
